snippet.textDisplay:
If you are over sixty years of age and you become infected with the corona virus you will die. 




Death may be avoided if you can get

extraordinarily expensive and invasive hospital care and treatment. If you are
over sixty years of age and you become infected your chances of dying are 20
times greater than an infected person 
under sixty years of age. The world famous epidemiologist Anthony Fauci finally
said to an international audience in an international news conference what he
had not been allowed to say for a long time:





“The one
factor that makes the difference between the life and death of the infected is
age.”





 The shocking statistics are due to the high
rate of infection at the beginning of an outbreak.  At the beginning of an outbreak the
population regards the announcement of the threat of a pandemic as just fear
mongering, a nuisance.  People with no
understanding of the severity and virulence of the virus dismiss it by saying
“ït’s no worse than the common cold, those who heed the warnings are fools.”
Hence, they take no precautions and this attitude in the general population and
among political leaders as well allows the infection rate to soar at the
beginning of the outbreak. This huge number of cases overwhelms the hospital
system because the system cannot deal with such a high number of infected due
to a lack of beds and a lack of expensive oxygen therapy equipment. Those
infected over sixty years of age will die unless they receive extraordinary
hospital care which includes expensive special equipment of which most
hospitals do not have enough to treat the huge numbers of elderly who fall ill
during a pandemic. The elderly need oxygen therapy equipment in order to stay alive
and the hospitals, unable to treat patients without this expensive or difficult
to purchase equipment don’t admit the elderly infected and may even lock their
doors.  In Wuhan, without the necessary
beds and equipment they had no way to treat the massive numbers of sick and
dying that were suddenly begging for admittance to the hospitals. If you paid
any attention to the private videos coming out of Wuhan in January and February
you saw the numbers of people who took their elderly Mothers and Fathers,
Grandmothers and Grandfathers, Aunties and Uncles to hospitals which had no
choice but to lock them out.  A
particularly poignant video taken at Wuhan Central Hospital admissions desk
showed the admissions nurse admitting younger patients but repeatedly telling a
young man who had brought his sick father for treatment to take him home and
treat him at home. Repeatedly hospital after hospital in Wuhan had to close
their doors and people had to take their loved ones home and, without proper
equipment (ventilators and oxygen apparatus) to care for them they died.  The videos of these encounters smuggled out
of China are pitiful.  The Chinese
authorities could see that the problem was not the virus but the lack of
equipment and facilities to treat it and they were forced to take the
extraordinary step of locking down all of Wuhan and other large cities for 30
days in order to reduce social contact and thereby slow the infection rate
(less contact among the populace means less infected) and give the Government
Medical System the necessary time needed to equip hospitals with the devices
necessary for proper oxygen therapy for the elderly.  Old people who become infected invariably
need oxygen tubes placed through the nose directly into the lungs in order to
get the oxygen needed to breathe. Because of the pain and pneumonia which
accompanies the infection it is extremely difficult and painful to breathe.
Intubation equipment, ventilation machines and oxygen tanks are needed to keep
the elderly alive while their body fights off the infection. Some people under
sixty who have other conditions like asthma or diabetes will also need this extraordinary
treatment.  But the young should not be
complacent, it’s not “just like a common cold.’’  Its’s more like having ten common colds all at
the same time, and as mentioned above, it can be deadly even for the young.  Most younger cases of infection can safely be
treated at home with pain medication like Paracetamol.  In interviews those who have recovered from
the illness speak of the overwhelming pain it causes.  Antibiotics might also be needed because
pneumonia often develops to accompany the viral infection.  There are now videos from Wuhan of these
younger patients screaming and crying in pain.





Your local
hospital may be fully equipped to treat elderly patients, but how many?  50? 
100?  1000?  What is cost effective for the hospital nearest
you? Is your hospital trying right now to increase the amount of ventilators
they have?  Will you be one of the
elderly left out without the equipment necessary to save your life?





The best
defence is isolation.  If you go into
quarantine and remain isolated you reduce your chance of infection.  Stay indoors.   Do not go out.  Get whatever you usually buy in quantity
enough for a long quarantine and isolate yourself indoors.  This will take time to prepare: long storage
food items like beans, oats, breakfast cereals mixes, instant soups, buillon
condiments salt, pepper, breakfast cereal, powdered milk, canned goods, frozen
foods, dried foods, coffee tea, green tea of course, medications you regularly
take, multiple vitamins, vitamin c, B12, and D,  soap, laundry powder, toiletries and stores of
everything needed for living.  Whatever
you need to go out to get from time to time you must now have on hand so that
you don’t have to go out. Get it now while you can. During a city state or
national lockdown will they let you out to go to the market? Maybe, but if you
break quarantine to do some shopping you risk becoming infected and those you
interact with will not be concerned that infection is a perilously greater risk
for someone elderly.  They still think
its’s just a common cold. Prepare now so that you don’t have to go out later.
It’s a big job, but, being elderly means you are informed and you know how to
get things done.  Get them done quickly
and get inside and stay safe.  Apologize
to your friends for not being able to see them for a long time and tell your
friends you will be in quarantine for an extended period and why, and that they
should stay in touch by phone and stay themselves in quarantine, especially if
they are elderly.  Then, remain yourself in
quarantine until the health authorities announce that the danger is over.  Harsh? 
Yes. But, if you are over sixty years of age isolation quarantine is
very probably the only protection you have against a very real mortal enemy
especially if the medical system you live with is a for profit enterprise.(Note)
If you are poor, for profit medicine is already a mortal enemy.  Maybe The World will be lucky and warmer
weather will stop the virus in its tracks. But you are older and wiser and know
better than to wager so much on such an ephemeral “maybe.” Prepare instead, and
hope that the virus is stopped short and that you will be doubly lucky and not
have to go shopping for several months.





Note: Medicine is over two thousand years old and is above
all else the patrimony of all humanity. 
To sell it violates the human rights of every human being.  To profiteer during a pandemic on test kits,
masks, ventilators or even lie and jocky for political advantage with medical
advice is immoral.





Prepare, be
well, be good, Be Happy,





Best of luck
abd Happiness, Mike
